 what factors determine the perceived fairness of those distributions? What social and psychological forces underlie determinations that certain uses of property are reasonable? What remedies do property owners prefer? The Psychology of Property Law explains how assumptions about human judgement, decision-making and behavior have shaped different property rules and examines to what extent these assumptions are supported by the research. Employing key findings from psychology, the book considers whether property law’s goals could be achieved more successfully with different rules. In addition, the book highlights property laws and conflicts that offer productive areas for further behaviorally-informed research. The book critically addresses several topics from property law for which psychology has a great deal to contribute. These include ownership and possession, legal protections for residential and personal property, takings of property by the state, redistribution through property law, real estate transactions, discrimination in housing and land use, and remedies for injury to property.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAcquisition of property. 0aPossession (Law). 0aPossessiveness. 0aPropertyxPsychological aspects. 0aProperty. 0aRight of property. 0aThings (Law). 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  aDiscrimination.  aFair Housing Act.  aLockean labor theory.  aOwnership.  aPossession.  aPreferences.  aPrejudice.  aRemedies.  aSchemas.  aStereotype.  aTaxes.  aadaptation.  aadverse possession.  aanchoring.  aapplied psychology.  abailments.  abankruptcy exemptions.  abehavioral law and economics.  abounded rationality.  abundle of rights.  acognitive biases.  acultural differences.  adebiasing.  adeception.  adictator game.  adisparate impact.  adual age